f <i>emplassein</i> ‘to shape or form’; the term was carried over into building terminology to mean ‘bonding agent’).","English: variant from a common pronunciation of <b>Plastow</b>, a habitational name from any of various places called Plaistow (in East London, Derbyshire, Sussex, and elsewhere), from Old English <i>plegestōw</i> ‘place where people gather for sport or play’. This can also be a variant of   Plaisted   (through interchangeable use of the Old English elements <i>stōw</i> and <i>stede</i>, both meaning ‘place’, in earlier times).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from German <i>Pflaster</i> ‘(street) pavement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Plaisted","meanings":["English (mainly Kent): topographic name from Middle English <i>plei(e)</i> ‘play, game, performance’ + <i>stede</i> ‘place, location’ (Old English <i>plegstede</i>, <i>plægstede</i>). The surname may be for someone who lived near a place for physical or theatrical play, or from a place so named, such as Chapel Plaster in Wiltshire. Compare   Plaster   2."]},{"name":"Plasterer","meanings":["English: occupational name for a plasterer, from Old French <i>plastrier</i> or an agent derivative of Middle English <i>plaster</i> (see   Plaster   1).","Americanized form of German <b>Pflasterer</b>, an occupational name for a paver or a <i>Pflästerer</i>, a manufacturer of plasters for wounds, from an agent derivative of Middle High German <i>pflaster</i> (see   Plaster  )."]},{"name":"Playle","meanings":["English (Essex): apparently a habitational name from an unidentified place called in Old English <i>plega</i> ‘play, sport’ + <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’. Compare   Plaster   2."]},{"name":"Plasters","meanings":["English: variant of   Plaster  ."]}]},{"name":"Elinor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705202,"age":5,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":16,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705206,"age":18,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":32,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705210,"age":47,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":67,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Elinor Pilaster was born in 1553, in Tetbury, Gloucestershire, England. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Edward Norris. She died in 1621, in England, at the age of 68."},"et":{"1553–1621":"1553–1621","1552–1603":"1552–1603","1577–Male":"1577–Surnud","1588–1621":"1588–1621","October 1603":"oktoober 1603","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1577":"1577","1588":"1588","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1553":"1553","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","1603":"1603","Tetbury, Gloucestershire, England":"Tetbury, Gloucestershire, England","England":"England","Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, England":"Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, England"},"fi":{"1553–1621":"1553–1621","1552–1603":"1552–1603","1577–Male":"1577–Kuollut","1588–1621":"1588–1621","October 1603":"lokakuu 1603","1571":"1571","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1600":"1600","1577":"1577","1588":"1588","1621":"1621","1620":"1620","1553":"1553","1585":"1585","1552":"1552","1603":"1603","Tetbury, Gloucestershire, England":"Tetbury, Gloucestershire, England","England":"England","Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, England":"Scrooby, Nottinghamshire, Engla